00:00:23.630 --> 00:00:29.220
Now, today we get to move on
from integral formulas and

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:34.620
methods of integration back
to some geometry.

00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:38.290
And this is more or less going
to lead into the kinds of

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:43.120
tools you'll be using in
multivariable calculus.

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:46.510
The first thing that we're going
to do today is discuss

00:00:46.510 --> 00:00:58.220
arc length.

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:02.940
Like all of the cumulative sums
that we've worked on,

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:06.710
this one has a storyline and the
picture associated to it,

00:01:06.710 --> 00:01:09.360
which involves dividing
things up.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:12.650
If you have a roadway, if you
like, and you have mileage

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:19.400
markers along the road, like
this, all the way up to, say,

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:28.060
sn here, then the length along
the road is described by this

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:30.560
parameter, s.

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:32.930
Which is arc length.

00:01:32.930 --> 00:01:38.080
And if we look at a graph of
this sort of thing, if this is

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:42.390
the last point b, and this is
the first point a, then you

00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:50.460
can think in terms of having
points above x1, x2, x3, etc.

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:53.940
The same as we did with
Riemann sums.

00:01:53.940 --> 00:02:00.710
And then the way that we're
going to approximate this is

00:02:00.710 --> 00:02:09.470
by taking the straight lines
between each of these points.

00:02:09.470 --> 00:02:12.260
As things get smaller and
smaller, the straight line is

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:15.210
going to be fairly close
to the curve.

00:02:15.210 --> 00:02:16.980
And that's the main idea.

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:20.050
So let me just depict one
little chunk of this.

00:02:20.050 --> 00:02:20.900
Which is like this.

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:24.530
One straight line, and here's
the curved surface there.

00:02:24.530 --> 00:02:26.940
And the distance along the
curved surface is what I'm

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:32.000
calling delta s, the change in
the length between, so this

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.920
would be s2 - s1 if I
depicted that one.

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:43.170
So this would be delta s is,
say s. si - si - 1, some

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:45.240
increment there.

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:50.500
And then I can figure out what
the length of the orange

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:51.750
segment is.

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:54.630
Because the horizontal
distance is delta x.

00:02:54.630 --> 00:02:57.290
And the vertical distance
is delta y.

00:02:57.290 --> 00:03:04.390
And so the formula is that the
hypotenuse is delta x ^2 +

00:03:04.390 --> 00:03:06.470
delta y ^2.

00:03:06.470 --> 00:03:09.420
Square root.

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:11.870
And delta s is approximately
that.

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:13.980
So what we're saying is
that delta s ^2 is

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:16.370
approximately this.

00:03:16.370 --> 00:03:21.870
So this is the hypotenuse.

00:03:21.870 --> 00:03:23.500
Squared.

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:29.520
And it's very close to the
length of the curve.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:35.120
And the whole idea of calculus
is in the infinitesimal, this

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:44.150
is exactly correct.

00:03:44.150 --> 00:03:48.010
So that's what's going to
happen in the limit.

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:52.000
And that is the basis for
calculating arc length.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.060
I'm going to rewrite that
formula on the next board.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:59.460
But I'm going to write it in
the more customary fashion.

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.200
We've done this before,
a certain amount.

00:04:02.200 --> 00:04:04.460
But I just want to emphasize
it here because this

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:09.390
handwriting is a little
bit peculiar.

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:11.710
This ds is really
all one thing.

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:15.690
What I really mean is to put
the parenthesis around it.

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:16.660
It's one thing.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:19.070
It's not d * s, it's ds.

00:04:19.070 --> 00:04:20.020
It's one thing.

00:04:20.020 --> 00:04:20.940
And we square it.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:23.940
But for whatever reason people
have gotten into the habit of

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:26.650
omitting the parentheses.

00:04:26.650 --> 00:04:28.070
So you're just going to have
to live with that.

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:31.050
And realize that this is not d
of s ^2 or anything like that.

00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:33.470
And similarly, this is a single
number, and this is a

00:04:33.470 --> 00:04:34.130
single number.

00:04:34.130 --> 00:04:36.060
Infinitesimal.

00:04:36.060 --> 00:04:41.300
So that's just the way that this
idea here gets written in

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:42.350
our notation.

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:44.710
And this is the first time we're
dealing with squares of

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:46.070
infinitesimals.

00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:47.600
So it's just a little
different.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.490
But immediately the first thing
we're going to do is

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:51.750
take the square root.

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:55.780
If I take the square root,
that's the square root of dx

00:04:55.780 --> 00:04:58.640
^2 + dy ^2.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:00.640
And this is the form
in which I always

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:02.400
remember this formula.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:07.030
Let's put it in some brightly
decorated form.

00:05:07.030 --> 00:05:13.200
But there are about 4, 5, 6
other forms that you'll derive

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:16.110
from this, which all mean
the same thing.

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:18.520
So this is, as I say, the
way I remember it.

00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:20.270
But there are other ways
of thinking of it.

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:23.070
And let's just write a
couple of them down.

00:05:23.070 --> 00:05:27.380
The first one is that you
can factor out the dx.

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:29.480
So that looks like this.

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:34.680
1 + (dy / dx)^2.

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:37.630
And then I factored
out the dx.

00:05:37.630 --> 00:05:39.820
So this is a variant.

00:05:39.820 --> 00:05:43.780
And this is the one which
actually we'll be using in

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:47.490
practice right now
on our examples.

00:05:47.490 --> 00:05:57.260
So the conclusion is that the
arc length, which if you like

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:06.800
is this total sn - s0, if you
like, is going to be equal to

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:13.180
the integral from a to b
of the square root of 1

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:20.490
+ (dy / dx)^2 dx.

00:06:20.490 --> 00:06:26.680
In practice, it's also
very often written

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:29.090
informally as this.

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:30.750
The integral ds.

00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:34.490
So the change in this little
variable s, and this is what

00:06:34.490 --> 00:06:40.410
you'll see notationally
in many textbooks.

00:06:40.410 --> 00:06:42.430
So that's one way of writing it,
and of course the second

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:45.950
way of writing it which is
practically the same thing is

00:06:45.950 --> 00:06:50.040
square root of 1 +
f ' ( x^2) dx.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:52.330
Mixing in a little bit
of Newton's notation.

00:06:52.330 --> 00:06:57.250
And this is with y = f (x).

00:06:57.250 --> 00:07:03.310
So this is the formula
for arc length.

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:05.770
And as I say, I remember
it this way.

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:09.060
But you're going to have to
derive various variants of it.

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:11.120
And you'll have to use
some arithmetic to

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:12.650
get to various formulas.

00:07:12.650 --> 00:07:15.190
And there will be more later.

00:07:15.190 --> 00:07:16.030
Yeah, question.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:20.820
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:27.350
PROFESSOR: OK, the question is,
is f ' (x)^2 = f '' (x).

00:07:27.350 --> 00:07:31.020
And the answer is no.

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:33.090
And let's just see what it is.

00:07:33.090 --> 00:07:39.360
So, for example, if f ( x) = x
^2, which is an example which

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:46.450
will come up in a few minutes,
then f ' (x) = 2x and f ' ( x

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:52.380
)^2 = = (2x), which is 4x ^2.

00:07:52.380 --> 00:07:56.180
Whereas f '' ( x) is equal to,
if I differentiate this

00:07:56.180 --> 00:07:58.750
another time, it's equal to 2.

00:07:58.750 --> 00:08:03.440
So they don't mean
the same thing.

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:04.700
The same thing over here.

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:07.360
You can see this dy / dx, this
is the rate of change of y

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:08.190
with respect to x.

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:09.780
The quantity squared.

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:11.400
So in other words, this
thing is supposed to

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:13.450
mean the same as that.

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:13.800
Yeah.

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:19.580
Another question.

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:25.660
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:25.660 --> 00:08:28.850
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
you got a little nervous

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:30.430
because I left out
these limits.

00:08:30.430 --> 00:08:32.800
And indeed, I did that on
purpose because I didn't want

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:34.530
to specify what was going on.

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:37.230
Really, if you wrote it in terms
of ds, you'd have to

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:40.760
write it as starting at s0 and
ending at sn to be consistent

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:42.180
with the variable s.

00:08:42.180 --> 00:08:45.730
But of course, if you write it
in terms of another variable,

00:08:45.730 --> 00:08:46.940
you put that variable in.

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:48.990
So this is what we do when we
change variables, right?

00:08:48.990 --> 00:08:51.570
We have many different choices
for these limits.

00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:54.530
And this is the clue as to
which variable we use.

00:08:54.530 --> 00:08:59.060
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:02.180
PROFESSOR: Correct. s0 and
sn are not the same

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:03.310
thing as a and b.

00:09:03.310 --> 00:09:05.290
In fact, this is xn.

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:07.740
And this x0, over here.

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:08.990
That's what a and b are.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:13.250
But s0 and sn are mileage
markers on the road.

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:15.450
They're not the same thing as
keeping track of what's

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:16.950
happening on the x axis.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:20.240
So when we measure arc length,
remember it's mileage along

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:27.980
the curved path.

00:09:27.980 --> 00:09:32.410
So now, I need to give
you some examples.

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:40.820
And my first example is going
to be really basic.

00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:45.630
But I hope that it helps to give
some perspective here.

00:09:45.630 --> 00:09:49.560
So I'm going to take the example
y = m x, which is a

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:52.550
linear function, a
straight line.

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:58.630
And then y ' would = m, and so
ds is going to be the square

00:09:58.630 --> 00:10:02.650
root of 1 + (y ') ^2 dx.

00:10:02.650 --> 00:10:10.840
Which is the square root
of 1 + m ^2 dx.

00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:17.700
And now, the length, say, if
we go from, I don't know,

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:24.990
let's say 0 to 10, let's say.

00:10:24.990 --> 00:10:29.620
Of the graph is going to be the
integral from 0 to 10 of

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:33.990
the square root of
1 + m ^2 dx.

00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:39.910
Which of course is just 10
square root of 1 + m ^2.

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:41.810
Not very surprising.

00:10:41.810 --> 00:10:43.360
This is a constant.

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:45.570
It just factors out and
the integral from 0

00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:51.210
to 10 of dx is 10.

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:54.340
Let's just draw a
picture of this.

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:57.530
This is something which
has slope m here.

00:10:57.530 --> 00:10:59.020
And it's going to 10.

00:10:59.020 --> 00:11:02.340
So this horizontal is 10.

00:11:02.340 --> 00:11:05.930
And the vertical is 10 m.

00:11:05.930 --> 00:11:08.030
Those are the dimensions
of this.

00:11:08.030 --> 00:11:12.050
And the Pythagorean theorem says
that the hypotenuse, not

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:15.530
surprisingly, let's draw it in
here in orange to remind

00:11:15.530 --> 00:11:17.840
ourselves that it was the same
type of orange that we had

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:21.850
over there, this length
here is the square

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:27.160
root of 10 ^2 + (10m)^2.

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:31.400
That's the formula for
the hypotenuse.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:38.520
And that's exactly
the same as this.

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:40.540
Maybe you're saying duh,
this is obvious.

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:44.160
But the point that I'm trying
to make is this.

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:48.220
If you can figure out these
formulas for linear functions,

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:52.510
calculus tells you how to do
it for every function.

00:11:52.510 --> 00:11:56.370
The idea of calculus is that
this easy calculation here,

00:11:56.370 --> 00:12:01.100
which you can do without any
calculus at all, all of the

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:05.050
tools, the notations of
differentials and limits and

00:12:05.050 --> 00:12:07.430
integrals, is going to
make you be able to

00:12:07.430 --> 00:12:10.040
do it for any curve.

00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:12.000
Because we can break things
up into these little

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.070
infinitesimal bits.

00:12:13.070 --> 00:12:16.380
This is the whole idea of all of
the methods that we had to

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:18.620
set up integrals here.

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:25.770
This is the main point
of these integrals.

00:12:25.770 --> 00:12:32.480
Now, so let's do something
slightly more interesting.

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:41.140
Our next example is going to be
the circle, so y = square

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:48.590
root of 1 - x ^2.

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:51.820
If you like, that's the
graph of a semicircle.

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:57.040
And maybe we'll set it
up here this way.

00:12:57.040 --> 00:13:00.030
So that the semicircle goes
around like this.

00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:02.310
And well start it
here at x = 0.

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:04.250
And we'll go over to a.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:06.560
And we'll take this little
piece of the circle.

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:08.150
So down to here.

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:11.850
If you like.

00:13:11.850 --> 00:13:16.010
So here's the portion of the
circle that I'm going to

00:13:16.010 --> 00:13:17.660
measure the length of.

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:19.110
Now, we know that length.

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:20.160
It's called arc length.

00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:21.760
And I'm going to give it a name,
I'm going to call it

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:23.400
alpha here.

00:13:23.400 --> 00:13:39.640
So alpha's the arc length
along the circle.

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:42.660
Now, let's figure
out what it is.

00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:44.560
First, in order to do this,
I have to figure

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:45.970
out what y ' is.

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:47.960
Or, if you like, dy / dx.

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:50.680
Now, that's a calculation that
we've done a number of times.

00:13:50.680 --> 00:13:52.830
And I'm going to do it
slightly faster.

00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:55.180
But you remember it gives
you a square root in the

00:13:55.180 --> 00:13:57.160
denominator.

00:13:57.160 --> 00:14:00.070
And then you have the derivative
of what's inside

00:14:00.070 --> 00:14:01.180
the square root.

00:14:01.180 --> 00:14:02.260
Which is - 2x.

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:05.320
But then there's also 1/2,
because in disguise it's

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:07.840
really (1 - x ^2)^2 1/2.

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:11.160
So we've done this calculation
enough times that I'm not

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:12.500
going to carry it
out completely.

00:14:12.500 --> 00:14:14.290
I want you to think
about what it is.

00:14:14.290 --> 00:14:16.950
It turns out to - x up
here, because the

00:14:16.950 --> 00:14:22.890
1/2 and the 2 cancel.

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:27.410
And now the thing that we have
to integrate is this arc

00:14:27.410 --> 00:14:30.190
length element, as
it's called. ds.

00:14:30.190 --> 00:14:32.970
And that's going to be
the square root of

00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:38.350
1 + (y ') ^2 dx.

00:14:38.350 --> 00:14:41.060
And so I'm going to have to
carry out the calculation,

00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:42.970
some messy calculation here.

00:14:42.970 --> 00:14:47.020
Which is that this is 1
+ ( - x / square root

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:49.610
of 1 - x ^2) ^2.

00:14:49.610 --> 00:14:52.410
So I have to figure out what's
under the square root sign

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:55.740
over here in order to carry
out this calculation.

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:58.570
Now let's do that.

00:14:58.570 --> 00:15:03.310
This is 1 + x ^2 / 1 - x ^2.

00:15:03.310 --> 00:15:06.140
That's what this
simplifies to.

00:15:06.140 --> 00:15:08.700
And then that's equal
to, over a common

00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:11.190
denominator, (1 - x ^2).

00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:13.580
1 - x ^2 + x^2.

00:15:13.580 --> 00:15:16.500
And there is a little bit
of simplification now.

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:19.190
Because the 2x ^2's cancel.

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:28.640
And we get 1 / 1 - x^2.

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:36.350
So now I get to finish off the
calculation by actually

00:15:36.350 --> 00:15:40.580
figuring out what the
arc length is.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:42.460
And what is it?

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:47.630
Well, this alpha is equal
to the integral

00:15:47.630 --> 00:15:51.990
from 0 to a of ds.

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:53.510
Well, it's going to
be the square root

00:15:53.510 --> 00:15:55.110
of what I have here.

00:15:55.110 --> 00:15:57.950
This was a square, this is just
what was underneath the

00:15:57.950 --> 00:15:58.710
square root sign.

00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:01.500
This is 1 + (y ') ^2.

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:03.270
Have to take the square
root of that.

00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:13.350
