00:39:41.210 --> 00:39:43.820
And then there are two
other dimensions.

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:47.080
If we have a curved surface,
there's no other dimension

00:39:47.080 --> 00:39:56.460
left to form a shell.

00:39:56.460 --> 00:39:59.760
But basically, you can chop
things up into any bits that

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:00.670
you can actually measure.

00:40:00.670 --> 00:40:04.020
That you can figure out
what the area is.

00:40:04.020 --> 00:40:08.270
That's the main point.

00:40:08.270 --> 00:40:10.960
Now, I said we were going to,
we've just launched into

00:40:10.960 --> 00:40:12.910
three-dimensional space.

00:40:12.910 --> 00:40:21.650
And I want to now move on to
other space-like phenomena.

00:40:21.650 --> 00:40:26.780
But we're going to do this.

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:31.980
So this is also a preparation
for 18.02, where you'll be

00:40:31.980 --> 00:40:34.840
doing this a tremendous
amount.

00:40:34.840 --> 00:40:49.530
We're going to talk now about
parametric equations.

00:40:49.530 --> 00:40:57.150
Really just parametric curves.

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:59.320
So you're going to see this
now and we're going to

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:00.890
interpret it a couple of times,
and we're going to

00:41:00.890 --> 00:41:02.580
think about polar coordinates.

00:41:02.580 --> 00:41:05.920
These are all preparation for
thinking in more variables,

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:08.570
and thinking in a different
way than you've

00:41:08.570 --> 00:41:09.720
been thinking before.

00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:12.520
So I want you to prepare
your brain to make

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:14.130
a transition here.

00:41:14.130 --> 00:41:16.540
This is the beginning
of the transition to

00:41:16.540 --> 00:41:21.580
multivariable thinking.

00:41:21.580 --> 00:41:26.350
We're going to consider
curves like this.

00:41:26.350 --> 00:41:29.850
Which are described with x being
a function of t and y

00:41:29.850 --> 00:41:31.410
being a function of t.

00:41:31.410 --> 00:41:35.630
And this letter t is called
the parameter.

00:41:35.630 --> 00:41:38.150
In this case you should think
of it, the easiest way to

00:41:38.150 --> 00:41:39.700
think of it is as time.

00:41:39.700 --> 00:41:43.840
And what you have is what's
called a trajectory.

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:48.090
So this is also called
a trajectory.

00:41:48.090 --> 00:41:52.410
And its location, let's
say, at time 0, is

00:41:52.410 --> 00:41:54.590
this location here.

00:41:54.590 --> 00:41:58.310
Of (0, y ( 0)), that's
a point in the plane.

00:41:58.310 --> 00:42:00.640
And then over here, for
instance, maybe

00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:04.410
it's (x ( 1), y (1)).

00:42:04.410 --> 00:42:07.630
And I drew arrows along here to
indicate that we're going

00:42:07.630 --> 00:42:10.110
from this place over
to that place.

00:42:10.110 --> 00:42:16.190
These are later times. t = 1
is a later time than t = 0.

00:42:16.190 --> 00:42:20.560
So that's just a very casual,
it's just the way

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:22.680
we use these notations.

00:42:22.680 --> 00:42:33.040
Now let me give you the first
example, which is x = a cos t,

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:40.340
y = a sin t.

00:42:40.340 --> 00:42:43.140
And the first thing to figure
out is what kind

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:45.490
of curve this is.

00:42:45.490 --> 00:42:48.770
And to do that, we want to
figure out what equation it

00:42:48.770 --> 00:42:52.000
satisfies in rectangular
coordinates.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.880
So to figure out what curve this
is, we recognize that if

00:42:54.880 --> 00:42:57.720
we square and add.

00:42:57.720 --> 00:43:01.300
So we add x ^2 to y^2, we're
going to get something very

00:43:01.300 --> 00:43:02.670
nice and clean.

00:43:02.670 --> 00:43:11.990
We're going to get a^2 cos
^2 t + a ^2 sin ^2 t.

00:43:11.990 --> 00:43:13.500
Yeah that's right, OK.

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:16.842
Which is just a ^2 (cos^2
+ sin ^2), or

00:43:16.842 --> 00:43:19.230
in other words a^2.

00:43:19.230 --> 00:43:23.450
So lo and behold, what
we have is a circle.

00:43:23.450 --> 00:43:27.840
And then we know what
shape this is now.

00:43:27.840 --> 00:43:33.850
And the other thing I'd like
to keep track of is which

00:43:33.850 --> 00:43:35.990
direction we're going
on the circle.

00:43:35.990 --> 00:43:40.020
Because there's more to this
parameter then just the shape.

00:43:40.020 --> 00:43:42.570
There's also where we
are at what time.

00:43:42.570 --> 00:43:44.000
This would be, think
of it like the

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.610
trajectory of a planet.

00:43:46.610 --> 00:43:52.060
So here, I have to do this by
plotting the picture and

00:43:52.060 --> 00:43:53.250
figuring out what happens.

00:43:53.250 --> 00:44:02.770
So at t = 0, we have (x, y) is
equal to, plug in here (a cos

00:44:02.770 --> 00:44:06.190
0, a sin 0).

00:44:06.190 --> 00:44:10.570
Which is just a * 1
+ a * 0, so a0.

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:11.830
And that's here.

00:44:11.830 --> 00:44:14.660
That's the point (a, 0).

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:18.810
We know that it's the
circle of radius a.

00:44:18.810 --> 00:44:20.360
So we know that the curve
is going to go

00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:22.140
around like this somehow.

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:26.390
So let's see what happens
at t = pi / 2.

00:44:26.390 --> 00:44:32.500
So at that point, we have
(x,y) = ( a cos pi /

00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:37.310
2, a sin pi / 2).

00:44:37.310 --> 00:44:41.580
Which is (0, a), because
sine of pi / 2 = 1.

00:44:41.580 --> 00:44:43.190
So that's up here.

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:46.100
So this is what happens
at t = 0.

00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:49.220
This is what happens
at t = pi / 2.

00:44:49.220 --> 00:44:51.390
And the trajectory clearly
goes this way.

00:44:51.390 --> 00:44:54.800
In fact, this turns out
to be t = pi, etc.

00:44:54.800 --> 00:44:58.330
And it repeats at t = 2 pi.

00:44:58.330 --> 00:45:01.600
So the other feature that we
have, which is qualitative

00:45:01.600 --> 00:45:11.560
feature, is that it's
counterclockwise.

00:45:11.560 --> 00:45:17.020
No the last little bit is going
to be the arc length.

00:45:17.020 --> 00:45:19.030
Keeping track of
the arc length.

00:45:19.030 --> 00:45:23.390
And we'll do that next time.

